            "ignore": false,
            "order": 5,
            "anno_id": 1,
            "text": " As a starting point to obtain input parameters for the MLFT modeling, self-consistent DFT in the linear density approximation is sufficient, which we performed using the FPLO package [\\[81\\]](#page-9-1). The Brillouin zone was sampled by a  $2 \\times 2 \\times 2$  k-point mesh. The exchange-correlation potential was treated in LDA, with the scalar relativistic functional according to Ref. [82](#page-9-1). We have used the experimental crystal structure from Ref. [31](#page-9-1): rhombohedral space group  $R\\overline{3}m$  (166),  $a = 4.37$  Å and  $c = 101.83$  Å, slightly distorted octahedral Mn coordination with Mn-Te bond length of 3.00 Å ( $C_{3\\text{v}}$  crystal field symmetry). We obtained Wannier orbitals as input for MLFT by downfolding to a basis set of Mn  $3d$ , Te  $5p$  and Bi  $6p$  orbitals in an energy window from  $-6$  to 3 eV including an exponential decaying tail with a decay of 1 eV at the boundaries of the selected energy range.  The MLFT calculations were performed using the Quanty package [\\[44, 83, 84\\]](#page-10-1) within the CI scheme considering the nominal  $2p^63d^5$  (Mn<sup>2+</sup>) configuration and two further charge-transfer states  $d^6\\overline{L}$  and  $d^7\\overline{L}^2$ . The spectral contributions from the split ground-state terms were weighted by a Boltzmann factor for  $T = 2 \\text{ K}$ . The meanfield effective potential was modeled by an exchange field estimated from the  $T_c$  of 12 K. Instrumental and lifetime effects were taken into account by a Gaussian broadening of 0.35 eV (FWHM) and an *E*-dependent Lorentzian profile of 0.15 – 0.35 eV (FWHM).",
